# Data Preprocessing

## Census Data

### Goals

* Gather annual demographic data at the 5-digit zip code level for all zip codes in New York City.
* Analyse changes in income over our observation period (2012-2022 inclusive) and select candidate zip codes for further exploration.
* Create and save a dataframe containing the relevant demographic data for each selected zip code.

### Tool

Visual Studio Code, Python, By-Request Census API Key

### Datasets

Raw Data
[https://www.census.gov/data/developers/data-sets/acs-5year.html](https://www.census.gov/data/developers/data-sets/acs-5year.html)

Cleaned Data
`brooklyn_selected_zips.csv`

### Processing steps (as seen in `census.ipynb`)

API Extraction
Pulled 20+ variables including median household income, poverty rate, and racial composition.

Error Handling
Identified and replaced Census-specific error codes (e.g. -666666666) with NaN values to avoid affecting averages.

Data Formatting
Converted ZIP codes and Year values to standard string/integer formats to create a key for consistent merging.

Export
Saved a cleaned year over year dataframe to `brooklyn_selected_zips.csv`.

---

## 311 Data

### Goals

* Clean the massive dataset, extracting only potentially relevant variables for the three selected zip codes.
* Prepare all variable columns for year by year analysis.
* Create and save a dataframe that merges the annual 311 variable measurements with the Census data.

### Tool

Visual Studio Code, Python

### Datasets

Raw Data
`raw311data.csv`

Full dataset:
[https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1jlRPKzeqzUxn2A3depW_ZSNS9aE4w93p?usp=share_link](https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1jlRPKzeqzUxn2A3depW_ZSNS9aE4w93p?usp=share_link)

Cleaned Data
`cleaned311.csv`, `preCategories.csv`

Merged Data
`merged.csv`, `LDAdata.csv`

### Processing Steps

(in `merge.ipynb`, `QSS20_clean_combine.ipynb`, and `categorization2.ipynb`)

Initial Data Joining
Merged and reordered 11 annual datasets into one chronologically combined file.

Column Cleaning
Removed irrelevant columns and renamed the remaining ones.

Temporal Engineering
Extracted year values from timestamps and calculated the average duration (resolution time) of complaints.

Aggregating
Grouped data by zip code and year.

Manual Mapping
Identified all unique complaint descriptions and created conditional logic to sort complaints by type and agency.

Agency Categorization
Created a dictionary distributing agencies into 6 categories.

Complaint Type Indicators
Sorted complaint instances into 10 categories such as housing, noise, sanitation, parks, finance, business, infrastructure, and education.

### NLP Refinement (`categorization2.ipynb`)

Text Preparation
Used **spaCy** to tokenize and lemmatize complaint descriptions.

Topic Modeling
Ran an **LDA (Latent Dirichlet Allocation)** model via **gensim**.

Comparison
Compared LDA results with manual categorization to ensure consistency.

---

# Analyses

### Analysis 1 — Census Data Collection and Demographic Trends

Variables
ZIP code, year, median household income, racial composition, population.

Findings
Census API data from ACS 5-year estimates allows observation of demographic and income changes over time across neighborhoods.

### Analysis 2 — Neighborhood Selection Based on Income and Demographic Patterns

Variables
ZIP code, median household income, income growth.

Findings
Brownsville remained consistently low income, Park Slope remained high income, and Bushwick experienced strong income growth and demographic transition.

### Analysis 3 — Cleaning and Aggregating NYC 311 Complaint Data

Variables
complaint type, ZIP code, creation date.

Findings
The dataset was filtered to the three ZIP codes and complaints were aggregated by ZIP code and year.

### Analysis 4 — Construction of ZIP-Year Panel Dataset

Variables
ZIP code, year, ZIPYEAR identifier.

Findings
ZIPYEAR allowed merging complaint data with Census demographics to create a panel dataset.

### Analysis 5 — Topic Modeling and Complaint Categorization

Variables
complaint type text.

Findings
LDA topic modeling identified clusters such as housing problems, sanitation issues, park concerns, and noise complaints.

### Analysis 6 — Categorized Complaint Counts by ZIP-Year

Variables
complaint category, ZIP code, year.

Findings
Complaint counts were aggregated and merged with demographic variables.

### Analysis 7 — Longitudinal Complaint Trend Analysis

Variables
complaint category counts, ZIP code, year.

Findings
Brownsville shows higher survival complaints while Park Slope shows more quality of life complaints.

### Analysis 8 — Quality-of-Life vs Survival Complaint Ratio

Variables
QoL complaint counts, survival complaint counts.

Findings
Bushwick’s ratio increases over time, indicating a shift toward lifestyle complaints during gentrification.

### Analysis 9 — Regression Analysis of Demographic Predictors

Variables
complaint rates, median household income, percent White non-Hispanic population, inequality indicators.

Findings
Higher income and demographic shifts correlate with higher rates of quality-of-life complaints.

