# Discussion

## Challenges and Limitations

### a. Small sample size

Our analysis focuses on only three neighborhoods, limiting regression power.

### b. Complexity of complaint classification

Hundreds of complaint types introduce classification uncertainty.

### c. Reporting bias in 311 data

Lower-income neighborhoods may underreport problems.

### d. ACS rolling averages

ACS uses 5-year rolling averages, smoothing rapid demographic change.

---

## Future Work

### x. Expanding geographic coverage

Include additional ZIP codes to increase statistical power.

### y. Improved natural language processing

Use more advanced NLP techniques for complaint classification.

### z. Incorporating additional urban data

Integrate housing prices, rent burden, or eviction filings.

### w. Causal identification strategies

Use difference-in-differences or event study approaches.

---

# Related Work

* **Legewie & Schaeffer (2016)** — 311 complaints act as instruments of boundary making.
* **Legewie (2024)** — conflict peaks in neighborhoods experiencing rapid demographic change.
* **Beck (2020)** — gentrification linked to increased policing via 311 complaints.
* **Stolper (2024)** — quality-of-life calls more likely to trigger police intervention in neighborhoods of color.
* **Kontokosta & Hong (2021)** — high-poverty areas underreport infrastructure issues.
* **Zukin et al. (2009)** — incoming residents reshape public space through retail and lifestyle change.
* **NYU Furman Center (2024)** — survival complaints concentrated in poorer neighborhoods.

